description: From Latin prīvātus (“bereaved, deprived, set apart from”), perfect passive participle of prīvō (“I bereave, deprive”), from prīvus (“private, one's own, peculiar”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *per; compare prime, prior, pristine. Doublet of privy.

adjectives.description: private (comparative more private, superlative most private)

entries.meaning: Belonging to, concerning, or accessible only to an individual person or a specific group.
examples: Her address is private; you can't have it.

entries.meaning: Not in governmental office or employment.
examples: He quit public life, living quietly as a private citizen.

entries.meaning: Not publicly known; not open; secret.
examples: The identity of the beneficiaries of the trust is private.

entries.meaning: Protected from view or disturbance by others; secluded.
examples: Can we go somewhere more private?
He is a very private person.

entries.meaning: (US, of a room in a medical facility) Not shared with another patient.
(not comparable, object-oriented programming) Accessible only to the class itself or instances of it, and not to other classes or even subclasses.
A soldier of the lowest rank in the army.
A doctor working in privately rather than publicly funded health care.
examples: In the cities and towns of California, privates are pressuring county governments to close or reduce in size their hospitals and to pay private hospitals for the care of low-income patients. Thus everything is stacked against public hospitals.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) A secret message; a personal unofficial communication.

examples: Nor must I be unmindful of my private.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) One not invested with a public office.
(usually in the plural) A private lesson.
examples: If you want to learn ballet, consider taking privates.

verbs.description: private (third-person singular simple present privates, present participle privating, simple past and past participle privated)

entries.meaning: (Internet, transitive) To make something hidden from the public (without deleting it permanently).
